-- Malaysia Stocks: Ajiya, Malaysian Pacific, Media Shoppe, Pantech
-- B y   G a n   Y e n   K u a n
-- 2012-01-19T09:31:59Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-19/malaysia-stocks-ajiya-malaysian-pacific-media-shoppe-pantech.html
Shares of the following companies
had  unusual  moves in  Malaysia trading . Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the close in  Kuala Lumpur .  The  FTSE Bursa Malaysia KLCI Index (FBMKLCI)  fell 0.57 point, or less
than 0.1 percent, to 1,516.81.  Semiconductor stocks:  Malaysian Pacific Industries Bhd. (MPI) 
 jumped 13 percent to 3.15 ringgit, its largest gain
since March 13, 2009.  Unisem (M) Bhd.  (UNI MK) advanced 5.6
percent to 1.32 ringgit, its highest close since Sept. 2.  RHB Capital Bhd. upgraded both stocks to “market perform”
from “underperform” on expectations of a stronger recovery in
the country’s semiconductor industry in the second half of this
year, Yap Huey Chiang, an analyst, wrote in a report today.  Ajiya Bhd. (AJY)  , a supplier of building materials,
climbed 2.4 percent to 1.70 ringgit, the most since Oct. 28.
Fourth-quarter net income grew 8.8 percent to 4.5 million
ringgit ($1.5 million) from a year earlier, the company said in
a stock exchange filing.  Hua Yang Bhd. (HYB)  , a property developer, added 1.5
percent to 1.32 ringgit, its highest close since July 14. Third-
quarter net income almost doubled to 14.6 million ringgit from
7.7 million ringgit a year earlier, the company said in a stock
exchange filing.  The Media Shoppe Bhd. (MSHP)  , a developer of Internet
sites, surged 156 percent to 23 sen, its highest close since
August 2006. This prompted the stock exchange regulator to issue
a query on the stock’s “unusual” market activity, according to
a company statement.  Pantech Group Holdings Bhd. (PGHB)  , a steel-products
maker, gained 2.9 percent to 53.5 sen, its highest close since
Aug. 15. Third-quarter net income jumped 70 percent to 10.3
million ringgit, the company said in a statement.  Poly Glass Fibre (M) Bhd.  (PGF MK), a manufacturer of
fiber-glass wool, rose 11 percent to 35 sen, its largest
increase since Oct. 19. The company’s third-quarter net income
almost tripled to 3.4 million ringgit from 1.2 million ringgit a
year earlier, according to a stock exchange filing.  Xidelang Holdings Ltd. (XIDE)  , a China-based footwear
maker, dropped 3.9 percent to 37.5 sen, its biggest decline
since Jan. 11. The company is planning a private placement of as
much as 10 percent of its share capital, Xidelang said in a
statement.  To contact the reporter on this story:
